SIMPLE: spin
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spin
<hw>Spin</hw> <pr>(sp⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spun</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> (<mark>Archaic</mark>
<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Span</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>); <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Spinning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>spinnan</ets>; akin to D. & G. <ets>spinnen</ets>, Icel. & Sw.
<ets>spinna</ets>, Dan. <ets>spinde</ets>, Goth. <ets>spinnan</ets>, and
probably to E. <ets>span</ets>. ⟦root⟧170. Cf. <er>Span</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>, <er>Spider</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw out, and
twist into threads, either by the hand or machinery; <as>as, to
<ex>spin</ex> wool, cotton, or flax; to <ex>spin</ex> goat's hair</as>;
to produce by drawing out and twisting a fibrous material.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the yarn she [Penelope] <qex>spun</qex> in Ulysses' absence
did but fill Ithaca full of moths.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw out tediously; to form by a slow process, or
by degrees; to extend to a great length; -- with <xex>out</xex>; <as>as,
to <ex>spin</ex> out large volumes on a subject</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do you mean that story is tediously <qex>spun</qex> out?</q>
<rj><qau>Sheridan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To protract; to spend by delays; <as>as, to
<ex>spin</ex> out the day in idleness</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By one delay after another they <qex>spin</qex> out their whole
lives.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to turn round rapidly; to whirl; to twirl;
<as>as, to <ex>spin</ex> a top</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To form (a web, a cocoon, silk, or the like) from
threads produced by the extrusion of a viscid, transparent liquid, which
hardens on coming into contact with the air; -- said of the spider, the
silkworm, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>To shape, as malleable sheet
metal, into a hollow form, by bending or buckling it by pressing against
it with a smooth hand tool or roller while the metal revolves, as in a
lathe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To spin a yarn</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to tell
a story, esp. a long or fabulous tale.</cd> -- <col><b>To spin
hay</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to twist it into ropes for
convenient carriage on an expedition.</cd> -- <col><b>To spin street
yarn</b></col>, <cd>to gad about gossiping.</cd>
<mark>[Collog.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spin
<hw>Spin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
practice spinning; to work at drawing and twisting threads; to make yarn
or thread from fiber; <as>as, the woman knows how to <ex>spin</ex>; a
machine or jenny <ex>spins</ex> with great exactness.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They neither know to <qex>spin</qex>, nor care to toll.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move round rapidly; to whirl; to revolve, as a
top or a spindle, about its axis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Round about him <qex>spun</qex> the landscape,⟦br⟧
Sky and forest reeled together.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With a whirligig of jubilant mosquitoes <qex>spinning</qex> about
each head.</q> <rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To stream or issue in a thread or a small current or
jet; <as>as, blood <ex>spins</ex>from a vein</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move swiftly; <as>as, to <ex>spin</ex> along the
road in a carriage, on a bicycle, etc.</as></def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spin
<hw>Spin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of spinning;
<as>as, the <ex>spin</ex> of a top; a <ex>spin</ex> a
bicycle</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Kinematics)</fld> <def>Velocity of rotation about
some specified axis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Politics)</fld> <def>an interpretation of an event
which is favorable to the interpreter or to the person s/he supports. A
person whose task is to provide such interpretations for public
relations purposes is called a <er>spin doctor</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- <col><b>go for a spin</b></col>, <col><b>take a spin</b></col>,
<cd>take a trip in a wheeled vehicle, usu. an automobile.</cd> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spina bifida</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
